'''''Inocybe cookei''''', [[common name|commonly known]] as the '''straw fibrecap''', is a species of [[mushroom]] in the [[Inocybaceae]] family. It was first described in 1892 by [[Giacomo Bresadola]], and is named in honour of [[Mordecai Cubitt Cooke]]. The species can be found in Europe, Asia and North America. It produces small mushrooms of an [[ochre]] colour, with a prominent [[umbo (mycology)|umbo]], fibres on the [[pileus (mycology)|cap]] and a distinctive bulb at the base of the [[stipe (mycology)|stem]]. It grows from soil in [[mixed forest|mixed woodland]], and is encountered in summer and autumn, though is not common. Ecologically, it feeds through use of [[ectomycorrhiza]]. ''Inocybe cookei'' has been described as both [[mushroom poisoning|toxic]] and non-toxic, but either way, is not advised for consumption.

