''Inocybe cookei'' was first described by [[Giacomo Bresadola]] in 1892;<ref name="urlMycoBank: Inocybe cookei"/> the [[specific name (botany)|specific epithet]] ''cookei'' honours the British mycologist [[Mordecai Cubitt Cooke]].<ref name=Rea1922>{{cite book |title=British Basidiomycetaceae: a Handbook to the Larger British Fungi |author=[[Carleton Rea|Rea, Carleton]] |year=1922 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge, UK |page=205 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/17128040}}</ref> Mycologists J. Stangl and J. Veselský described ''Inocybe kuthanii'' in 1979,<ref>{{cite journal |title=''Inocybe kuthanii'' sp. nov. Eine neue Art in Sektion ''Rimosae'', Stirps '' Cookei'' Heim gehörend. (Beiträge zur Kenntnis seltenerer Inocyben. Nr. 15) |journal=Ceská Mykologie |year=1979 |author1=Stangl, J. |author2=Veselský, J. |volume=33 |issue=3 |pages=134–37 |language=German}}</ref> which was later described as a [[variety (botany)|variety]] of ''Inocybe cookei'' (''Inocybe cookei'' var. ''kuthanii'') by Thom Kuyper in 1986,<ref>{{cite journal |title=A revision of the genus ''Inocybe'' in Europe. I. Subgenus ''Inosperma'' and the smooth-spored species of subgenus ''Inocybe'' |journal=Persoonia Supplement |year=1986 |author=Kuyper, T.W. |volume=3 |page=51}}</ref> but [[MycoBank]] now lists both names as [[Synonym (taxonomy)|synonyms]] of ''I.&nbsp;cookei''.<ref name="urlMycoBank: Inocybe cookei">{{cite web |url=http://www.mycobank.org/MycoTaxo.aspx?Link=T&Rec=223073 |title=''Inocybe cookei'' |publisher=[[MycoBank]]. International Mycological Association|accessdate=2010-12-23}}</ref> The mushroom is [[common name|commonly known]] as the straw fibrecap.<ref name="Sterry"/>

Within ''[[Inocybe]]'', it is placed within the [[subgenus]] ''Inosperma'',<ref name="Larsson"/> and was previously categorised within the [[section (botany)|section]] ''Rimosae''.<ref name="Kew"/> However, [[Molecular phylogenetics|phylogenetic analysis]] has shown that section ''Rimosae'' as formerly defined does not form a [[monophyletic]] group (that is, descended from a single exclusive ancestor), and former ''Rimosae'' species are better grouped into two [[cladistics|clades]], ''Maculata'' and ''Rimosae''. Phylogenetic analysis has placed the species in the clade ''Maculata''. Other species joining ''I.&nbsp;cookei'' in the ''Maculata'' clade include ''[[Inocybe maculata|I.&nbsp;maculata]]'', ''[[Inocybe quietiodor|I.&nbsp;quietiodor]]'', ''[[Inocybe rhodiola|I.&nbsp;rhodiola]]'', ''[[Inocybe adaequata|I.&nbsp;adaequata]]'', and ''[[Inocybe erubescens|I.&nbsp;erubescens]]''.<ref name="Larsson">{{cite journal |author1=Larsson, E. |author2=Ryberg, M. |author3=Moreau, P.-A. |author4=Mathiesen, Å. Delcuse |author5=Jacobsson, S. |year=2009 |title=Taxonomy and evolutionary relationships within species of section ''Rimosae'' (''Inocybe'') based on ITS, LSU and mtSSU sequence data |journal=Persoonia |volume=23 |pages=86–98 |url=http://www.persoonia.org/Issue/23/08.pdf |doi=10.3767/003158509X475913 |format=PDF}}</ref>

==Description==
''Inocybe cookei'' has a conical or bell-shaped [[pileus (mycology)|cap]] of between {{convert|2|and|5|cm|in}} in diameter. As the mushrooms age, the cap becomes flatter, and an [[umbo (mycology)|umbo]] becomes prominent. The margin of the cap frequently cracks towards the centre. The cap is an [[ochre]] colour, and the upper surface is covered in long fibres.<ref name="Phillips"/> The silky fibres thickly cover the cap, starting and the centre and extending to the cap's margin.<ref name="Jordan"/> The species has a whitish or ochre [[stipe (mycology)|stem]] of {{convert|30|to|60|mm|in}} in height by {{convert|4|to|8|mm|in}} in thickness.<ref name="Phillips"/> There is a distinctive [[wikt:marginate|marginate]] bulb at the base of the stem,<ref name="Kibby"/> and no [[Annulus (mycology)|ring]].<ref name="Jordan"/> The [[Trama (mycology)|flesh]] is white, becoming yellow with age.<ref name="Jordan"/> ''Inocybe cookei'' mushrooms have closely packed adnexed [[lamella (mycology)|gills]] (gills that are attached to the stem only on part of their depth).<ref name="Phillips">{{cite book |title= Mushrooms and Other Fungi of Great Britain and Europe|author= Phillips, Roger|year= 1981|publisher= [[Pan Books]]|location= London|isbn= 0-330-26441-9|page=149}}</ref><ref name="Pegler"/> Gills on young mushrooms are whitish, then become a grey-tinged pale ochre before becoming [[cinnamon]] yellow.<ref name="Jordan"/>

===Microscopic features===
''Inocybe cookei'' leaves a [[Snuff (tobacco)|snuff]]-brown [[spore print]]. The [[spore]]s themselves are [[bean]]-shaped,<ref name="Phillips"/> measuring from {{convert|5.5|to|10|um}} by {{convert|4|to|6|um}}. The walls of the spores (which are around {{convert|0.5|um}} thick) can be smooth or slightly wrinkled, and there is a distinct depression just above the hilum (the scar where the spore was once attached to the [[basidium]]).<ref name="Kew">{{cite journal |title=Basidiospore form in the British species of ''Inocybe'' |author1=Pegler, D.N. |author2=Young, T.W.K. |journal=Kew Bulletin |year=1972 |pages=499–537 |volume=26 |issue=3 |doi=10.2307/4120316}}</ref> The basidia are four-spored, and the thin-walled, gill-edge [[cheilocystidia]] are pear-shaped.<ref name="Jordan"/>

