The species can be differentiated from the similar ''[[Inocybe praetervisa|I. praetervisa]]'' by its spores; the latter "has irregular, lumpy spores".<ref name="Kibby"/> ''[[Inocybe rimosa]]'', the split fibrecap, is also similar in appearance; the rarer ''I.&nbsp;cookei'' can be differentiated by the smell of honey and the marginate bulb.<ref name="Sterry"/> The colouration, as well as the thick stem with a bulb, are features shared by two other species of ''Inocybe''; ''[[Inocybe mixtilis|I.&nbsp;mixtilis]]'' and ''[[Inocybe cryptocystis|I.&nbsp;cryptocystis]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Two new species of ''Inocybe'' (Cortinariales) from Spain, with a comparative type study of some related taxa |author=Esteve-Raventós, Fernando |journal=Mycological Research |volume=105 |issue=9 |pages=1137–43 |year=2001 |doi=10.1016/s0953-7562(08)61978-4}}</ref> Another fragrant ''Inocybe'' is ''[[Inocybe pyriodora|I.&nbsp;pyriodora]]'', which has an odor resembling cinnamon, or ripe pears in mature specimens; unlike ''I.&nbsp;cookei'', it lacks a bulb at the base of its stem, and bruises a reddish colour when handled or with age.<ref name=Arora1986>{{cite book |author=Arora, D. |authorlink=David Arora |title=Mushrooms Demystified: a Comprehensive Guide to the Fleshy Fungi |publisher=[[Ten Speed Press]] |location=Berkeley, California |year=1986 |page=459 |isbn=0-89815-169-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/mushroomsdemysti00aror_0 }}</ref>

==Distribution and habitat==
''Inocybe cookei'' is an occasional to frequent mushroom, found growing in mixed woodland on the ground.<ref name="Phillips"/><ref name="Kibby">{{cite book |title=Mushrooms and Toadstools of Britain and Northern Europe |last=Kibby |first=Geoffrey |year=2003 |publisher=[[Hamlyn (publishers)|Hamlyn]] |isbn=978-0-7537-1865-0 |page=99}}</ref> It is [[ectomycorrhizal]],<ref name="Mexico"/> and grows from summer to late autumn,<ref name="Phillips"/> solitarily or in "trooping groups".<ref name="Jordan">{{cite book |title=The Encyclopedia of Fungi of Britain and Europe |author=[[Michael Jordan (mycologist)|Jordan, Michael]] |year=2004 |publisher=[[Frances Lincoln]] |isbn=978-0-7112-2378-3 |page=287}}</ref> It has been recorded in Europe,<ref name="Phillips"/> Russia,<ref>{{cite journal |title=''Inocybe'' (Basidiomycota, Agaricales) from Kamchatka (Siberia, Russia): taxonomy and ecology |author1=Peintner, U |author2=Horak, E. |journal=Sydowia |pages=198–241 |volume=54 |issue=2 |year=2002}}</ref> China,<ref>{{cite book |title=The Macrofungus Flora of China's Guangdong Province |last=Bi |first=Zhishu |author2=Zheng, Guoyang |author3=Li, Taihui  |year=1993 |publisher=Chinese University Press |isbn=978-962-201-556-2 |page=428}}</ref> Mexico,<ref name="Mexico">{{cite journal |author1=Reverchon, Frédérique |author2=Ortega-Larrocea, María d.P. |author3=Pérez-Moreno, Jesús |author4=Peña-Ramírez, Víctor M. |author5=Siebe, Christina |year=2010 |title=Changes in community structure of ectomycorrhizal fungi associated with ''Pinus montezumae'' across a volcanic soil chronosequence at Sierra Chichinautzin, Mexico |journal=Canadian Journal of Forest Research |volume=40 |issue=6 |pages=1165–74 |doi=10.1139/X10-062}}</ref> and the United States.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Kauffman, C.H. |year=1917 |title=Tennessee and Kentucky Fungi |journal=[[Mycologia]] |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages= 159–66 |jstor=3753332 |issn=0027-5514 |doi=10.2307/3753332}}</ref>

==Toxicity and edibility==
''Inocybe cookei'' has been described as both [[mushroom poisoning|poisonous]] (due to the presence of [[muscarine]] compounds)<ref name="Kibby"/> and non-toxic.<ref name="Pegler"/> Consumption of mushrooms containing muscarine compounds could lead to a number of physiological effects, including: excess [[salivation]], [[lacrimation]], uncontrolled [[urination]] or [[defecation]], [[gastrointestinal problem]]s and [[emesis]] (vomiting); this array of symptoms may also be known by the acronym [[SLUDGE syndrome|SLUDGE]].<ref name="Hall">{{cite book |title=Edible and Poisonous Mushrooms of the World |last=Hall |first=Ian Robert |author2=Buchanan, Peter K. |author3=Stephenson, Steven L. |author4=Yun, Wang |author5= Cole, Anthony L.J.  |year=2003 |publisher=[[Timber Press]] |isbn=978-0-88192-586-9 |pages=108–109}}</ref> Other potential effects include a drop in [[blood pressure]], [[sweating]] and death due to [[respiratory failure]].<ref name="Hall"/> The flesh of the mushroom has a mild taste and a slight smell of honey.<ref name="Sterry">{{cite book |title= Complete Guide to British Mushrooms & Toadstools |author1=Sterry, Paul |author2=Hughes, Barry |year=2009 |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |isbn=978-0-00-723224-6 |page=192}}</ref><ref name="Phillips"/> Regardless of its actual toxicity or edibility, it is considered "best avoided".<ref name="Pegler">{{cite book |title=Mushrooms and Toadstools |last=Pegler |first=David N. |year=1983 |publisher=Mitchell Beazley Publishing |location=London |isbn=0-85533-500-9 |page=85}}</ref>

